folder: 321 East 34th Street, Manhattan, N.Y.
text:
A general view northwestward from the Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building at No. 321 E. 34th Street, north side, between First and Second Avenue, showing skyscrapers of the 42nd Street - Midtown area of Manhattan. From left to right (across the three views) they are: the 10 East 40th Street Building; the Lefcourt - Colonial Building (under construction); the Lincoln Building; the Chanin Building; and the Chrysler Building, (under construction). In the foreground is the Second Avenue "El" with a corner of St. Gabriels Park on the easterly side and tenements to the west.

September 10, 1929.
Views 1,2 and 3

P.L. Sperr

text:
321 E. 34th Street, north side, between First and Second Avenues, (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building), panoramic view westward.

These two views form a panoramic arrangement of the lower midtown zone between Madison Square and 42nd Street. Near the former are the insurance companies buildings, the Metropolitan and the New York Life. In the center (under construction) is a portion of the Empire State Building. To the right appear, the No. 10 E. 40th Street Building, the 500 Fifth Avenue Building (under construction) and the recently completed Lefcourt National Building (No. 295 Madison Avenue, completed late 1929;) In the left corner of No. 1 is a portion of the Second Avenue "El" with its 34th Street station and spur line at the left margin of No. 2. This last mentioned feature was demolished in the Summer of 1938. E. 35th Street is the thoroughfare passing thru the center of this view. Note the spire of the Church of the Epiphany at Lexington Avenue. This structure was razed about the same time as the 34th Street spur line.

Sept. 17, 1939
Views: 1 and 2

P. L. Sperr
title: General view - Manhattan - 34th Street (East) - Harriet Hubbard Ayer building.]

folder: 34th Street (East) - Harriet Hubbard Ayer building., Manhattan, NY
text:
321 East 34th Street, north side, between First and Second Avenues, (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) general view northward.

Three views forming a panoramic arrangement to show the 42nd Street-Midtown skyline of Manhattan. From left to right these buildings are: No. 10 E. 40th Street, No. 500 Fifth Avenue (under construction), The Leftcourt Colonial (No. 295 Madison Avenue), the Lincoln, the Chanin, the Chrysler and the News. Prior to 1929 none of these structures were standing.

Across the foreground runs the Second Avenue "El" passing the westerly side of St. Gabriel's Park. This garden and play area is between E. 35th and 36th Streets. In 1939, this will undergo radical changes as the new 38th Street-East River Tunnel approach will pass thru same to an entrance on 34th Street.

P. L. Sperr

September 17, 1930
Views: 1-2-3

folder: 34th Street (East) - Harriet Hubbard Ayer building., Manhattan, NY
text:
321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view westward) and viewing to the north, across Second Avenue and its "El" line.

On this side of same, appears, the westerly portion of St. Gabriel's Park (35th-36th Street's) and the future plaza of the Midtown-Queens Tunnel (36th-37th Street's).

At the right background beyond this section of Murray Hill, are the skyscrapers forming the 42nd Street outline. The bases of these in View 3 are, from left to right respectively, the Lincoln, the Chanin, the Chrysler and the News Buildings.

October 13, 1939
Views 1, 2, 3

P. L. Sperr

text:
321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building), north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view northeastward) across the westerly half of St. Gabriel's Park and the Second Avenue "El," towards the midtown sector.

At the latter point appears the prominent Chrysler and the News Buildings. Under construction in the mid-ground is the plaza approach to the Midtown-Queens Tunnel. The sole remaining building at this site is the St. Gabriel's branch of the New York Public Library. This is to be demolished early in 1940.

October 13, 1939
Views 1, 2, 3

P. L. Sperr

text:
321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view north and northeastward across the future plaza entrance of the Midtown-Queens Tunnel. This will included the entire 36th-37th Street block between the aforementioned Avenues. The low buildings framing the distant edge are on the north side of East 37th Street. To the right is First Avenue and it's New York Edison Company power plant. Beyond are the distinctive apartment structures comprising Tudor City at 42nd Street.

October 13, 1939
Views 1, 2, 3

P. L. Sperr

text:
321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view northward) across St. Gabriel's Park and the future entrance to the Midtown-Queens Tunnel.

Both of these are between the aforementioned Avenues, the former occupying the 35th-36th block and the latter, the next block north. Buildings seen in the background framing the clearance, are on the north side of 37th Street. Tudor City is at 42nd St. The Hotel Woodstock of same is in the center.

October 13, 1939
Views 1, 2, 3
